{{nihongo||御伽草子|'''Otogi-zōshi'''}} are a group of about 350 Japanese prose narratives written primarily in the [[Muromachi period]] (1392–1573).  These illustrated short stories, which remain unattributed, together form one of the representative literary genres of the Japanese medieval era.

== Overview ==
{{transliteration|ja|Otogi-zōshi}} is a general term for narrative literature written between the [[Muromachi period]] (approximately 1336–1573) and the beginning of the [[Edo period]] (1603–1867).{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=498}} The term originates with a mid-Edo collection of 23 stories, titled {{nihongo||御伽文庫|Otogi Bunko}} or {{nihongo||御伽草紙/御伽草子|Otogi-zōshi}}.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=498}} It later came to denote other works of the same genre and period.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=498}} Modern scholarship sometimes distinguishes between "true" {{transliteration|ja|otogi-zōshi}}, covering only the 23 works included in the aforementioned collection, and other works that it instead terms {{nihongo||室町時代物語|Muromachi-jidai monogatari}} or {{nihongo||中世小説|chūsei shōsetsu}}.{{sfnm|1a1=Ichiko|1y=1983|1p=498}} 

